5
00:00:17,776 --> 00:00:20,717
I mean, you guys have an amazing lineup and it's going to be an awesome day.

6
00:00:20,737 --> 00:00:23,038
So it's such a pleasure to be here and actually kicking this thing off.

7
00:00:24,819 --> 00:00:26,480
For those of you who don't know me, I'm Richard Audin.

8
00:00:26,540 --> 00:00:29,382
I'm the lead animator at Guerrilla Games, and the talk will be about

9
00:00:29,442 --> 00:00:31,743
the animation process of the machines in Horizon Zero Dawn.

10
00:00:33,039 --> 00:00:38,101
A little bit about myself, I studied at the Utrecht School of Arts for animation and my

11
00:00:38,181 --> 00:00:40,162
main goal was always to become a feature film animator.

12
00:00:41,583 --> 00:00:45,805
So in my third year I was actually very lucky to have an animation internship at DNA Productions

13
00:00:45,865 --> 00:00:47,626
during their feature film The End Bullion.

14
00:00:49,147 --> 00:00:50,528
That was such an amazing experience.

15
00:00:50,588 --> 00:00:53,249
I mean, I learned so much about the animation industry,

16
00:00:53,829 --> 00:00:55,209
animation itself, the workflow,

17
00:00:55,269 --> 00:00:57,430
and I got to meet a lot of cool animators

18
00:00:57,450 --> 00:00:58,910
that eventually just sort of like spread out

19
00:00:58,950 --> 00:01:01,631
through the entire industry after DNA got closed down.

20
00:01:01,671 --> 00:01:04,532
So getting back to the Netherlands and graduating,

21
00:01:04,552 --> 00:01:06,633
I knew I wanted to be a feature film animator,

22
00:01:06,673 --> 00:01:08,293
but I knew my reel wasn't strong enough.

23
00:01:09,174 --> 00:01:13,615
So I figured, okay, let me just work on my own and hopefully see from there what will happen.

24
00:01:13,655 --> 00:01:19,817
But I still wanted to get some of that industry experience and the only studio that was actually doing something was Guerrilla Games in Amsterdam back then.

25
00:01:21,198 --> 00:01:26,020
And it was like ten minutes away from my house, so I figured, okay, let me just at least send in my review and we'll see what happens.

26
00:01:26,120 --> 00:01:30,341
And luckily enough, they called me up and said, yeah, you have an interview.

27
00:01:30,441 --> 00:01:33,342
And a couple of days later, I actually got hired as a junior animator on Killzone.

28
00:01:35,294 --> 00:01:39,040
The crazy thing is as soon as I started to work in-game, I just fell in love with that process so much

29
00:01:39,180 --> 00:01:42,967
that I knew I never wanted to do anything else and like 10 years later I'm still with Guerrilla Games.

30
00:01:45,051 --> 00:01:54,620
Did a little bit of finishing off on Killzone 2, but got to really get my hands on in Killzone 3 doing the first person weapons, the new ones, and the Brutal Melee system that they had.

31
00:01:55,400 --> 00:02:00,144
I skipped Killzone Shadowfall because I was already working on the R&D team for Horizon Zero Dawn.

32
00:02:00,605 --> 00:02:05,990
The only thing that I actually helped them out with, just because the schedule was so tight at the end of Shadowfall, that I had to help them out with some of the cinematics.

33
00:02:06,070 --> 00:02:10,434
But basically the last five years of my life have been all around Horizon Zero Dawn.

34
00:02:11,415 --> 00:02:14,258
Recently, we just finished the expansion, the Frozen Wild.

35
00:02:14,298 --> 00:02:17,761
So that's sort of me in a very short period.

36
00:02:18,442 --> 00:02:21,165
I'm going to start a little bit with how the project

37
00:02:21,205 --> 00:02:23,588
actually evolved on Horizon Zero Dawn and the initial idea

38
00:02:23,608 --> 00:02:24,288
and the back story.

39
00:02:24,889 --> 00:02:27,131
And I'll shortly discuss some of the prototyping phase that

40
00:02:27,172 --> 00:02:28,893
we went through, where we started exploring how these

41
00:02:28,933 --> 00:02:31,436
machines would actually move and how do it look.

42
00:02:32,577 --> 00:02:37,023
But then I'll just cover a lot of in-depth production of the machines with multiple topics

43
00:02:37,063 --> 00:02:40,988
like the team structure, reference, movement, and the tech behind it.

44
00:02:41,108 --> 00:02:44,873
And I'll finally end up with some of the polish pass that we did.

45
00:02:44,913 --> 00:02:49,218
But if you're not that familiar with the project or you just need a refresher, here are some

46
00:02:49,238 --> 00:02:49,979
snippets of the machine.

47
00:03:12,696 --> 00:03:16,399
I mean, how did this whole thing actually came about, right?

48
00:03:17,200 --> 00:03:21,282
Back in 2011, we just finished Guilds on 3 and Guerrilla really wanted to change the

49
00:03:21,302 --> 00:03:25,845
direction so we basically just went to Sony and said, hey, can we just explore something

50
00:03:25,886 --> 00:03:27,947
new and they just said, yeah, go for it, which was amazing.

51
00:03:30,911 --> 00:03:35,192
Basically what the studio did was they sent out a mail and they said okay if you have

52
00:03:35,212 --> 00:03:38,874
an idea just pitch it to us and you can actually pitch a whole game, you can just pitch a game

53
00:03:38,894 --> 00:03:43,035
mechanic and then eventually we'll just pick the top three that we like and we'll start

54
00:03:43,055 --> 00:03:43,775
exploring those.

55
00:03:43,995 --> 00:03:45,476
So roughly around...

56
00:03:47,577 --> 00:03:48,958
45, 50 ideas got pitched in a week,

57
00:03:49,298 --> 00:03:51,761
and Horizon was already the one that actually

58
00:03:51,941 --> 00:03:53,482
was standing out from the crowd from the beginning.

59
00:03:53,502 --> 00:03:55,103
It was just like such a cool setting,

60
00:03:55,144 --> 00:03:56,725
and the theme in Majestic was amazing,

61
00:03:56,785 --> 00:03:58,727
but it was also the scariest one to develop

62
00:03:58,767 --> 00:04:01,709
because it was already a third person open world game

63
00:04:01,729 --> 00:04:03,791
from the get go, and we were just this first person studio.

64
00:04:03,811 --> 00:04:04,872
Like, what do we know, right?

65
00:04:06,889 --> 00:04:14,053
We explored a little bit of the other two, so there were three, but then eventually we just ended up with Horizon because everybody was just drawn to that thing.

66
00:04:14,113 --> 00:04:24,440
And basically the pitch itself was nothing more than Earth being reclaimed by nature and it's now inhabited by these robotic machines that are now the dominant life species.

67
00:04:24,520 --> 00:04:29,563
And the gameplay itself was still a mystery at this point, it was just that backstory that everybody just was drawn to.

68
00:04:30,624 --> 00:04:34,365
Guerrilla put together a small R&D team of roughly around 25 people,

69
00:04:34,405 --> 00:04:35,846
and just a couple from every department,

70
00:04:35,966 --> 00:04:38,988
and we just needed to figure out what the gameplay was going to be about.

71
00:04:39,428 --> 00:04:44,330
I was already the one from the beginning to actually start working on the robots.

72
00:04:45,937 --> 00:04:50,141
Since it was such a new genre for us, we knew we needed to get some new insights.

73
00:04:50,201 --> 00:04:53,124
And for me personally, I actually never animated a quadruped before this game.

74
00:04:54,365 --> 00:04:56,627
So I had to become an expert really quickly.

75
00:04:56,667 --> 00:04:59,990
And luckily enough, Animation Mental was doing this Animals and Creatures course back then.

76
00:05:01,091 --> 00:05:04,894
where I learned tons about actually the approach of animating quadrupeds,

77
00:05:05,115 --> 00:05:07,637
the workflow, the rigs, all the different gates.

78
00:05:08,598 --> 00:05:09,479
So that was really nice.

79
00:05:09,579 --> 00:05:12,621
And then next to that, Guerrilla also hired a bunch of industry experts

80
00:05:12,681 --> 00:05:14,483
to start educating the studios.

81
00:05:14,543 --> 00:05:16,705
To give you some examples, we had Stuart Zimida over.

82
00:05:17,225 --> 00:05:19,486
who was a very famous paleontologist,

83
00:05:20,607 --> 00:05:22,448
to give us a class on animal anatomy.

84
00:05:22,868 --> 00:05:25,089
We had Matthew Lund from Pixar do a story class.

85
00:05:25,229 --> 00:05:27,950
We had Scott Eaton do a human anatomy course, for example.

86
00:05:28,690 --> 00:05:31,652
So those were really nice educational moments.

87
00:05:31,732 --> 00:05:34,793
And also what happened is we had to get a lot of hires

88
00:05:34,833 --> 00:05:35,934
in a lot of departments.

89
00:05:35,974 --> 00:05:37,354
So it was either for capacity reasons,

90
00:05:37,374 --> 00:05:38,495
just because we were understaffed.

91
00:05:38,855 --> 00:05:41,395
but also just because we had no knowledge of this game, right?

92
00:05:41,416 --> 00:05:45,697
So we hired a bunch of industry experts that had done these games already,

93
00:05:45,737 --> 00:05:48,838
so they could just start filling us up in the gaps that we were missing.

94
00:05:48,898 --> 00:05:53,339
And last but not least, study as much nature as possible.

95
00:05:53,359 --> 00:05:56,840
I think I've watched every BBC Nature Planet documentary out there,

96
00:05:57,340 --> 00:05:58,200
like 50 times already.

97
00:05:58,240 --> 00:06:01,261
And it was also like, it was just getting to know the behavior,

98
00:06:01,281 --> 00:06:02,622
but also the movement, etc.

99
00:06:02,682 --> 00:06:04,382
And you learn so much from this thing.

100
00:06:04,422 --> 00:06:06,363
And there's so many cool nature footage out there that...

101
00:06:07,543 --> 00:06:11,186
Yeah, that's something that we just did a lot during the course of this whole thing.

102
00:06:12,086 --> 00:06:14,428
So like I mentioned, we had no idea what the gameplay was, right?

103
00:06:14,488 --> 00:06:19,091
So we started with a small R&D team just to explore the possibilities in our prototyping

104
00:06:19,151 --> 00:06:19,391
phase.

105
00:06:20,677 --> 00:06:22,858
Basically the prototyping phase was all the search,

106
00:06:23,098 --> 00:06:24,259
okay, what is this gameplay?

107
00:06:24,399 --> 00:06:27,581
And the idea behind it was to go as fast as possible

108
00:06:27,601 --> 00:06:29,102
with a limited amount of development time

109
00:06:29,162 --> 00:06:30,603
and see what works and what doesn't work.

110
00:06:30,623 --> 00:06:32,865
And if it doesn't work, instantly throw it out.

111
00:06:33,025 --> 00:06:34,466
If it does work, just keep iterating on it

112
00:06:34,506 --> 00:06:35,587
until we actually have something

113
00:06:35,607 --> 00:06:38,689
that's sort of like a nice gameplay feature.

114
00:06:38,749 --> 00:06:40,830
And since our resources were so limited,

115
00:06:41,611 --> 00:06:43,492
we basically had to work with what we had

116
00:06:43,612 --> 00:06:45,373
or just create some super basic assets.

117
00:06:46,634 --> 00:06:46,754
So.

118
00:06:49,014 --> 00:06:50,956
We actually started out with this Lego Thunderjaw.

119
00:06:51,136 --> 00:06:53,758
And the player character is actually Jammer from Killzone 3,

120
00:06:54,119 --> 00:06:56,821
which was the only female character that we did up

121
00:06:56,881 --> 00:06:57,342
until that point.

122
00:06:57,382 --> 00:06:59,864
But we already knew from the first pitch that we wanted

123
00:06:59,884 --> 00:07:00,905
to have a female protagonist.

124
00:07:00,925 --> 00:07:03,547
So that was actually something that we were very much

125
00:07:03,627 --> 00:07:04,648
pushing to, to get this in.

126
00:07:04,688 --> 00:07:06,670
And looking back at this, it's actually crazy how many

127
00:07:06,690 --> 00:07:08,612
of the initial mechanics made it into the final game.

128
00:07:08,632 --> 00:07:10,994
I mean, there's charges there, there's close combats,

129
00:07:11,274 --> 00:07:13,396
and it's all super basic, but I still like to see it.

130
00:07:15,079 --> 00:07:18,204
Even in this movie, we actually already put in the option to shoot off the weapon of the

131
00:07:18,244 --> 00:07:20,847
Thunderjaw and then use it against himself with this awesome physics.

132
00:07:20,907 --> 00:07:21,288
Look at that.

133
00:07:25,654 --> 00:07:26,976
So after playing around with this.

134
00:07:31,627 --> 00:07:35,969
So after playing around with a lot of the ideas that we had, this just took a couple of months,

135
00:07:36,049 --> 00:07:41,531
we finally created our first proof of concept that we showed to the higher peeps of Sony, and it looked like this.

136
00:07:42,252 --> 00:07:44,373
And as you can see, the environment is a little bit more fleshed out,

137
00:07:44,413 --> 00:07:47,914
and we actually have a first proper Thunderjaw model, but everything is still very basic,

138
00:07:47,934 --> 00:07:50,996
and it's basically just a full playthrough of this boss battle,

139
00:07:51,516 --> 00:07:53,777
using all the mechanics that we developed up until that point.

140
00:07:54,437 --> 00:07:55,898
As you can see, there's actually traps there.

141
00:07:56,779 --> 00:07:58,640
The play is already setting tripwires as well.

142
00:07:59,340 --> 00:08:04,243
But then all the other stuff that you saw, like the charges, close combats, etc. etc. is actually in this.

143
00:08:04,303 --> 00:08:10,487
I showed this to Sony and they really liked where this was heading.

144
00:08:10,647 --> 00:08:12,068
So they said, yeah, just keep going.

145
00:08:14,169 --> 00:08:16,070
Find whatever you want to see, like what you want.

146
00:08:16,130 --> 00:08:20,793
And then eventually, this sort of like concept turned into the reveal trailer that you guys saw on E3 in 2015.

147
00:08:26,268 --> 00:08:49,581
Whoa, someone's angry.

148
00:08:49,841 --> 00:08:51,762
Alright, time to shut you down.

149
00:08:56,022 --> 00:09:00,144
So that whole track of finding the gameplay on the Thunderjaw

150
00:09:00,184 --> 00:09:01,905
took roughly around two years to get right.

151
00:09:01,945 --> 00:09:04,626
And the idea behind it is if we can actually have all the

152
00:09:05,306 --> 00:09:08,168
states and mechanics and everything that we want out of

153
00:09:08,208 --> 00:09:11,910
this big boss battle, and if it's still fun to play, we can

154
00:09:11,950 --> 00:09:14,591
just chop all the small pieces up and apply it to the

155
00:09:14,631 --> 00:09:15,332
smaller robots.

156
00:09:20,696 --> 00:09:25,617
So, that's why it actually took a very long time and that was kind of frustrating sometimes,

157
00:09:25,697 --> 00:09:28,218
but it definitely was worthwhile in the end.

158
00:09:28,958 --> 00:09:34,560
And so like during this stage as well, I started to actually search what the style and movement of these machines were going to be as well.

159
00:09:34,640 --> 00:09:39,361
And during our prototype phase, my art director actually sent me this video and said,

160
00:09:39,381 --> 00:09:41,762
yeah, this is what I think the robot should move like.

161
00:09:49,718 --> 00:09:51,840
And as you can see, it's actually very jittery and mechanical,

162
00:09:51,860 --> 00:09:54,602
and that's just because there's no ease-ins or ease-out on the movements.

163
00:09:54,742 --> 00:09:57,744
It's all these linear, grip and pneumatic parts

164
00:09:58,164 --> 00:10:01,987
that cause for a lot of overlap on this very unstable installation.

165
00:10:06,371 --> 00:10:07,291
I know, right? So sad.

166
00:10:09,850 --> 00:10:13,891
But just because of the fact that the movement is so unpredictable, that's the thing that he liked.

167
00:10:13,931 --> 00:10:17,852
And it reminded him of this sort of zombie-esque type of feeling to that machine.

168
00:10:17,872 --> 00:10:22,414
So with that video in mind, I started the prototype on this smaller bot that we were creating back then,

169
00:10:22,934 --> 00:10:26,035
which is also looking a lot more mechanical than the previous Thunderjaw.

170
00:10:26,995 --> 00:10:29,156
Unfortunately, I couldn't find my initial test anymore.

171
00:10:30,236 --> 00:10:32,717
But what I can tell you is that I never got it to look right.

172
00:10:33,757 --> 00:10:36,558
As soon as I thought I had something, I exported it to the game.

173
00:10:37,619 --> 00:10:41,063
in game it actually looked like there was a frame rate bug or like it was just a very

174
00:10:41,123 --> 00:10:42,325
bad attempt at stop motion.

175
00:10:42,365 --> 00:10:48,874
So I just started to tone it down and eventually sort of like found a nice middle ground into

176
00:10:48,894 --> 00:10:49,956
this walk cycle that I made.

177
00:10:51,717 --> 00:10:53,838
As you can see, it has this sort of like fluid motion,

178
00:10:53,898 --> 00:10:56,960
but it's still mechanical, and it does feel kind of creepy.

179
00:10:57,000 --> 00:10:59,222
So I was actually sort of happy with this.

180
00:10:59,242 --> 00:11:01,904
It's like, let me just sort of like start iterating on this.

181
00:11:01,964 --> 00:11:04,886
And then as soon as you actually go into higher speeds,

182
00:11:05,326 --> 00:11:06,287
everything is out the window.

183
00:11:06,327 --> 00:11:07,868
Just because you have that fast movement,

184
00:11:07,928 --> 00:11:09,469
it's almost impossible to actually keep

185
00:11:09,489 --> 00:11:11,391
this sort of like jittery mechanical motion.

186
00:11:11,431 --> 00:11:14,073
And the only thing that I actually tried to apply to

187
00:11:14,133 --> 00:11:16,795
is on that chest, and you just see it popping back and forth.

188
00:11:16,815 --> 00:11:18,736
But it was just like a last attempt

189
00:11:18,776 --> 00:11:20,817
trying to get something mechanical into this thing.

190
00:11:22,158 --> 00:11:27,480
On this turn on spot I tried it again, but to me it just became this cluster of movement noise to these things.

191
00:11:27,560 --> 00:11:31,281
And again in this jump, it's just completely out the window.

192
00:11:31,781 --> 00:11:36,682
Eventually I found that I was actually animating these things more and more like realistic animals with an occasional jitter.

193
00:11:37,643 --> 00:11:40,544
Or like not perfect spacing, especially in the starts and the settles.

194
00:11:41,124 --> 00:11:43,144
Because that's where you can actually have a little bit of a wind up time.

195
00:11:44,505 --> 00:11:48,929
It actually started to seem to fit the designs that we were making for the new machines as well,

196
00:11:48,949 --> 00:11:50,790
to actually make them move realistically.

197
00:11:50,850 --> 00:11:53,773
And it also started to relate to the player a lot more.

198
00:11:53,813 --> 00:11:57,796
So if you look at this grazer for example, which was our first terraforming robot,

199
00:11:58,196 --> 00:12:02,060
I started to animate that thing super close to a real deer antelope type of creature.

200
00:12:02,100 --> 00:12:06,063
And as soon as playtesters started fighting against these things,

201
00:12:06,083 --> 00:12:08,145
they actually felt bad to hunt them.

202
00:12:08,665 --> 00:12:09,726
Especially when they were limping.

203
00:12:09,806 --> 00:12:10,907
Oh, is it not looping? Sorry.

204
00:12:15,609 --> 00:12:17,351
It's not looping anymore, sorry.

205
00:12:18,692 --> 00:12:20,534
But let me see.

206
00:12:21,094 --> 00:12:22,996
But that actually is the fact that I actually started to

207
00:12:23,016 --> 00:12:24,057
feel bad for these things.

208
00:12:24,077 --> 00:12:26,639
That's actually something that was also incorporated into the

209
00:12:26,679 --> 00:12:29,882
story where Aloy is actually being brought up to be very

210
00:12:29,962 --> 00:12:32,084
respectful towards these mechanical creatures.

211
00:12:32,104 --> 00:12:35,487
So that was a nice combination of elements of coming together

212
00:12:35,527 --> 00:12:36,508
naturally in this process.

213
00:12:38,043 --> 00:12:41,285
The only robots that we actually did apply some of the robotic movement to was the ancient

214
00:12:41,325 --> 00:12:42,785
war class like this Deathbringer.

215
00:12:43,486 --> 00:12:46,927
Even here, it was just because it fitted the design and the behavior more.

216
00:12:47,648 --> 00:12:50,849
But on these things, we actually started to look more at industrial machines like they

217
00:12:50,909 --> 00:12:55,132
use in car factories, since they have that nice combination of fluid motion and mechanical

218
00:12:55,172 --> 00:12:55,772
stuff combined.

219
00:13:00,180 --> 00:13:02,541
So that whole track of defining the gameplay,

220
00:13:02,822 --> 00:13:04,103
going through this pre-production phase,

221
00:13:04,143 --> 00:13:05,704
searching for the style, was done at this point.

222
00:13:05,784 --> 00:13:08,206
And at the same time, the rest of the studio

223
00:13:08,226 --> 00:13:09,166
was done with Shadowfall.

224
00:13:09,186 --> 00:13:11,328
So the entire team basically transferred over to Horizon.

225
00:13:11,368 --> 00:13:12,989
And from a production point of view,

226
00:13:13,009 --> 00:13:15,511
it actually makes sense for the producers

227
00:13:15,551 --> 00:13:16,812
to have these dedicated teams.

228
00:13:16,852 --> 00:13:19,234
So we had a team robot, we had a team alien,

229
00:13:19,254 --> 00:13:20,595
we had a team living world, et cetera.

230
00:13:20,675 --> 00:13:23,177
And the nice thing for us was that we could actually

231
00:13:23,317 --> 00:13:25,118
only focus on the robots, and that was the only thing

232
00:13:25,138 --> 00:13:26,099
that we had to take care of.

233
00:13:27,408 --> 00:13:28,669
Before the team actually transferred over,

234
00:13:28,709 --> 00:13:30,210
I started to make a list as a guideline

235
00:13:30,230 --> 00:13:32,091
that we could hold up to our own work,

236
00:13:32,591 --> 00:13:34,552
but also made it very clear for the rest of the team

237
00:13:34,592 --> 00:13:36,032
what the intention of these things was.

238
00:13:36,112 --> 00:13:39,154
And for me, the first and foremost was that these things

239
00:13:39,234 --> 00:13:41,095
actually feel like they belong in the world, right?

240
00:13:41,115 --> 00:13:42,856
So to make them as believable as possible.

241
00:13:43,516 --> 00:13:44,796
I knew we were gonna end up with roughly

242
00:13:44,816 --> 00:13:45,537
around 25 to 30 robots, so...

243
00:13:48,415 --> 00:13:52,518
It was very important to me that they actually all felt unique with their own personality

244
00:13:52,558 --> 00:13:53,819
shine through within their movement.

245
00:13:54,780 --> 00:13:58,983
The third one was that I really wanted them to feel bulky with lots of weight, which turned

246
00:13:59,023 --> 00:14:02,786
out a lot harder in the end than I was thinking in the beginning because you can make them

247
00:14:02,826 --> 00:14:06,730
as bulky and heavy as you want, but if they're not responsive in terms of gameplay, your

248
00:14:06,850 --> 00:14:07,410
game sucks.

249
00:14:07,430 --> 00:14:10,973
So there's a lot of back and forward that we had to do in the end on this, but I'll

250
00:14:11,013 --> 00:14:11,974
cover that a little bit later.

251
00:14:12,714 --> 00:14:15,317
Last but not least, they should be very scary to fight against.

252
00:14:17,470 --> 00:14:20,172
So Team Robot, this is sort of like the list that was in there.

253
00:14:21,293 --> 00:14:25,095
Three AI coders, four to six animators, three visual designers, two asset artists,

254
00:14:25,175 --> 00:14:27,716
three game designers, three effects artists, two sound designers,

255
00:14:27,756 --> 00:14:29,817
and TechArt was always there to support us.

256
00:14:30,558 --> 00:14:33,019
Even on this, we had like three subgroups.

257
00:14:33,500 --> 00:14:38,142
So two animators, one designer, and one AI coder was just working on one machine,

258
00:14:38,182 --> 00:14:40,984
and we had three machines in production at the same time all the time.

259
00:14:41,024 --> 00:14:44,806
So there was a very steady flow of creating these machines.

260
00:14:45,847 --> 00:14:49,228
The way we worked was very much layered and we had multiple sign-off moments.

261
00:14:49,248 --> 00:14:59,412
So basically game design started with around 50 to 62 pages that basically described the basic functionality of the machines and what mix of animals they wanted to use as an inspiration.

262
00:15:00,132 --> 00:15:04,854
And eventually the game director chose roughly around 25 to 30 machines that he wanted to see in the final game.

263
00:15:05,874 --> 00:15:09,578
As soon as we had that information, Visual Design actually had enough to start working

264
00:15:10,559 --> 00:15:11,120
on their stuff.

265
00:15:11,220 --> 00:15:15,905
And instead of just drawing, they actually went straight into ZBrush, skid-bashing these

266
00:15:15,945 --> 00:15:17,426
things together to make mock-up models.

267
00:15:17,506 --> 00:15:22,011
And once they had their first pass done, it got into TechArt to be rigged, and we started

268
00:15:22,031 --> 00:15:22,692
to test it out.

269
00:15:22,892 --> 00:15:25,355
And it became this sort of like back and forward in a loop.

270
00:15:26,968 --> 00:15:28,028
between those three teams.

271
00:15:28,108 --> 00:15:30,329
And eventually we had that sign-off moment

272
00:15:30,349 --> 00:15:31,469
where the mock-up model was done,

273
00:15:31,869 --> 00:15:33,110
and then AssetArt could actually start

274
00:15:33,370 --> 00:15:34,730
making the high-res model while we could

275
00:15:34,750 --> 00:15:36,991
actually start animating on the mock-up model.

276
00:15:37,651 --> 00:15:39,111
By the time the designers were actually done

277
00:15:39,151 --> 00:15:41,632
with their low-level design, which was like a 60-pager

278
00:15:42,712 --> 00:15:44,973
book for each robot individual,

279
00:15:45,073 --> 00:15:46,493
and we could actually start animating

280
00:15:46,513 --> 00:15:48,194
the actual machines from that point on.

281
00:15:48,774 --> 00:15:50,694
As soon as we had a good chunk of animations done,

282
00:15:51,595 --> 00:15:52,855
we created the animation networks,

283
00:15:52,895 --> 00:15:54,355
which is something that all the animators

284
00:15:54,395 --> 00:15:55,676
at Guerrilla handled their own.

285
00:15:56,496 --> 00:15:59,497
We handed that off to AI to actually start working on the behavior and the combat.

286
00:15:59,577 --> 00:16:04,360
And here we got like that second circle of so like iterations based on feedback from all the teams.

287
00:16:04,760 --> 00:16:07,761
And eventually once we sort of like halfway through that production,

288
00:16:08,942 --> 00:16:11,463
effects and sound design got to do their best.

289
00:16:11,643 --> 00:16:15,605
And at the end of that track we had a alpha ready machine, what we called it.

290
00:16:16,965 --> 00:16:20,808
The nice thing from a production point of view was in terms of scheduling,

291
00:16:20,828 --> 00:16:22,489
that everything had the staggered approach.

292
00:16:22,789 --> 00:16:24,730
Everybody was just working one month behind each other.

293
00:16:24,790 --> 00:16:25,551
So yeah, always had.

294
00:16:25,591 --> 00:16:27,352
So nobody was actually waiting for each other.

295
00:16:28,233 --> 00:16:30,954
We just kept on going without actually ever stopping.

296
00:16:31,014 --> 00:16:35,517
And for us, like I said, two animators would work on one machine for three months,

297
00:16:35,677 --> 00:16:37,258
and then we had an alpha ready version.

298
00:16:38,479 --> 00:16:41,721
And that eventually ended up with 25 unique robots,

299
00:16:41,921 --> 00:16:42,902
sort of like ranging from...

300
00:16:44,284 --> 00:16:46,869
120 to 350 unique animations per robot,

301
00:16:46,949 --> 00:16:48,512
depending on how big the game design was.

302
00:16:49,474 --> 00:16:51,538
So I think that workflow actually turned out

303
00:16:51,779 --> 00:16:53,041
to be pretty successful for us.

304
00:16:55,052 --> 00:16:57,633
So when we actually started a new machine, of course,

305
00:16:57,653 --> 00:17:00,275
the first thing we started to do was to search for reference.

306
00:17:00,395 --> 00:17:05,377
And sometimes it was actually really obvious

307
00:17:05,397 --> 00:17:06,557
what the real-life counterpart was.

308
00:17:06,757 --> 00:17:08,898
We still wanted to keep into things with an open mind.

309
00:17:08,938 --> 00:17:10,779
And that meant doing a lot of research

310
00:17:10,819 --> 00:17:12,120
and really keeping our eyes open,

311
00:17:12,820 --> 00:17:14,881
which is where all those hours of nature footage

312
00:17:14,941 --> 00:17:15,801
really comes in handy.

313
00:17:17,634 --> 00:17:21,596
So if you look at the Bellowback, which is a transporting class machine that actually carries liquids.

314
00:17:22,117 --> 00:17:24,758
If you look at it and just break it down, it's basically just a bipedal animal.

315
00:17:24,798 --> 00:17:27,199
So, but it's not your most obvious creature design.

316
00:17:27,359 --> 00:17:29,741
So we just started to search for things like birds and kangaroos,

317
00:17:29,981 --> 00:17:35,244
and I stumbled upon this really nice piece of footage of an emu, so like fighting a kangaroo.

318
00:17:38,178 --> 00:17:41,660
And the thing that I liked about it is how much of a shape change and posture change

319
00:17:41,680 --> 00:17:42,340
is into that thing.

320
00:17:42,380 --> 00:17:43,340
And it's so fluid.

321
00:17:43,400 --> 00:17:46,761
And I really wanted to get some of that into the bellow back.

322
00:17:46,841 --> 00:17:50,242
And in the design document, it said that it actually needed to shoot projectiles.

323
00:17:50,823 --> 00:17:54,884
And instead of just having a boring shooting straight animation, I wanted to do something

324
00:17:54,924 --> 00:17:55,044
else.

325
00:17:55,084 --> 00:17:58,465
And a little bit further in the video, he's actually doing this sort of gesturing thing,

326
00:17:58,525 --> 00:18:00,926
but it reminded me of him actually throwing a baseball.

327
00:18:01,486 --> 00:18:02,066
So I figured, okay.

328
00:18:03,403 --> 00:18:08,101
Why don't we just throw out the projectiles and that basically just turn into this animation.

329
00:18:14,530 --> 00:18:19,934
So the Rock Breaker, this was an acquisition robot that had to mine for resources on the ground.

330
00:18:19,994 --> 00:18:24,576
And if you look at it, it's basically designed, at least from a visual design,

331
00:18:24,616 --> 00:18:30,400
it was based on a mole lizard type of character, but I know I never wanted to actually animate like that on land.

332
00:18:30,460 --> 00:18:32,301
And I had no idea what to do with him either.

333
00:18:32,741 --> 00:18:36,204
So we just started to work on the underground movement and actually the submerged type of movement,

334
00:18:36,224 --> 00:18:40,226
which is all based on worms, but I still had no idea what to do with him on land.

335
00:18:40,266 --> 00:18:40,446
And then...

336
00:18:41,347 --> 00:18:45,135
As soon as we had to make all those animations, I was actually walking around the studio and

337
00:18:46,137 --> 00:18:49,645
I'm not kidding, like somebody was actually watching a nature documentary on their screen

338
00:18:50,026 --> 00:18:51,809
of these two sea lions fighting each other and

339
00:18:54,440 --> 00:18:56,501
The thing that I liked about it is how heavy they look,

340
00:18:56,542 --> 00:18:57,983
but they're actually still pretty agile

341
00:18:58,003 --> 00:18:59,564
and there was so much power behind it.

342
00:18:59,584 --> 00:19:02,006
So I figured, okay, let me just do a test animation with it

343
00:19:02,046 --> 00:19:03,427
because it's still reminding me a little bit

344
00:19:03,447 --> 00:19:04,208
of that rock breaker.

345
00:19:04,688 --> 00:19:07,491
So I made this test animation and showed it to our art director

346
00:19:07,511 --> 00:19:08,652
to say, hey, what do you think about this?

347
00:19:08,712 --> 00:19:10,333
And then he loved the idea.

348
00:19:10,373 --> 00:19:12,735
So the entire ground movement was based on sea lions

349
00:19:12,755 --> 00:19:13,356
from that point on.

350
00:19:17,005 --> 00:19:19,787
So for the Frost Claw on the Frozen Wilds,

351
00:19:19,827 --> 00:19:21,949
I mean this thing was clearly designed with a bear in mind.

352
00:19:22,029 --> 00:19:25,232
And it was really nice to actually have that posture

353
00:19:25,252 --> 00:19:26,753
change going from walking on fours

354
00:19:26,773 --> 00:19:28,655
to going on a bipedal stance.

355
00:19:28,795 --> 00:19:30,676
So we started to look for a lot of footage of bears

356
00:19:30,877 --> 00:19:33,639
and we made a bunch of claw swipes and a bunch of roars.

357
00:19:33,699 --> 00:19:35,981
But it was all, to me, it was all very predictable

358
00:19:36,061 --> 00:19:37,702
and it never had that one characteristic

359
00:19:37,723 --> 00:19:39,384
that started to make this machine feel unique,

360
00:19:39,604 --> 00:19:40,385
in my opinion, so.

361
00:19:41,085 --> 00:19:43,206
I started to think, okay, what else can we actually do with him, right?

362
00:19:43,486 --> 00:19:47,427
And then I remembered my girlfriend having this huge weak spot for red pandas.

363
00:19:47,787 --> 00:19:49,868
And I thought, okay, those could be interesting, right?

364
00:19:49,888 --> 00:19:51,468
Let me just start looking for footage.

365
00:19:51,548 --> 00:19:57,390
And I found this piece of footage, where they're basically just doing these really cool rolls.

366
00:19:57,450 --> 00:20:01,451
And it's also something that you don't really expect out of the frost claw.

367
00:20:01,471 --> 00:20:05,472
So I figured, okay, they're basically like regular pandas, but they're so feisty.

368
00:20:06,918 --> 00:20:08,779
They actually can be really angry towards each other.

369
00:20:08,799 --> 00:20:09,600
So I really liked it.

370
00:20:09,640 --> 00:20:11,882
So I just tested out some of those rolls on the Frost Claw.

371
00:20:12,622 --> 00:20:15,084
And that's actually the moment when I started

372
00:20:15,104 --> 00:20:16,005
to click with the Skerritt.

373
00:20:16,025 --> 00:20:19,008
And I thought that this was the stuff that I really

374
00:20:19,048 --> 00:20:19,668
wanted out of this thing.

375
00:20:19,708 --> 00:20:21,289
Of course, I had to put a lot more weight on it.

376
00:20:22,070 --> 00:20:23,971
But that rolling thing was that one thing

377
00:20:23,991 --> 00:20:26,634
that actually made him stand out from the rest of the machines

378
00:20:26,654 --> 00:20:28,435
that we had done up until that point.

379
00:20:29,727 --> 00:20:32,527
And then the last example is on the long leg, which is a

380
00:20:32,567 --> 00:20:34,708
recon class that actually uses echolocation to

381
00:20:34,728 --> 00:20:35,468
scout for threats.

382
00:20:35,588 --> 00:20:38,709
And in the design document, there was this attack that

383
00:20:39,230 --> 00:20:40,730
said that it needed to do a scratch attack.

384
00:20:40,830 --> 00:20:43,031
And whenever I looked at this thing, it always reminded me

385
00:20:43,051 --> 00:20:43,971
of a very big chicken.

386
00:20:44,051 --> 00:20:47,752
So just for fun, I typed in chicken scratch in YouTube,

387
00:20:47,932 --> 00:20:49,973
and I found this really cool piece of footage.

388
00:20:53,074 --> 00:20:54,495
They're so angry at that lady.

389
00:20:58,015 --> 00:21:00,699
So I just straight copied it over to Doortoon to make this animation.

390
00:21:02,020 --> 00:21:03,783
I didn't even try to make something else out of it.

391
00:21:06,844 --> 00:21:08,505
So before we actually started the machine,

392
00:21:08,545 --> 00:21:11,085
we really tried to define what the main characteristics

393
00:21:11,105 --> 00:21:11,865
of a machine would be.

394
00:21:11,985 --> 00:21:14,026
And we just took a couple of words per machine

395
00:21:14,366 --> 00:21:15,586
to describe the overall behavior

396
00:21:15,606 --> 00:21:16,607
and personality of these things.

397
00:21:16,687 --> 00:21:18,487
And here's just a bunch of examples

398
00:21:18,507 --> 00:21:19,808
where we tried to distinguish them

399
00:21:19,868 --> 00:21:21,288
as much as possible from each other.

400
00:21:21,308 --> 00:21:22,288
So if you look at the watcher,

401
00:21:22,308 --> 00:21:26,129
he was supposed to be aware, always curious,

402
00:21:26,830 --> 00:21:28,030
but also very calculated.

403
00:21:28,810 --> 00:21:31,111
And then the shell walker, who's like this cargo...

404
00:21:32,011 --> 00:21:36,753
crap type of thing that's super protective of its cargo on its back.

405
00:21:36,793 --> 00:21:40,794
We just wanted him to be very grumpy and obsessed about that whole thing on his back.

406
00:21:40,834 --> 00:21:46,277
And then the stalker was supposed to be like this angry guy that's always into combat.

407
00:21:46,297 --> 00:21:49,958
So it was just like describing them with a couple of words so everybody knew which direction we

408
00:21:49,998 --> 00:21:54,560
needed to go. And as soon as we had a nice overview of what all these machines needed to be,

409
00:21:55,300 --> 00:21:56,641
the next thing that we actually did was...

410
00:21:57,941 --> 00:22:02,025
make personality videos which we call movie mood like sort of mood board videos and

411
00:22:02,966 --> 00:22:05,588
This is not so like straight-up reference for the animations

412
00:22:05,728 --> 00:22:08,650
It's more to actually communicate what the characteristics of the machines

413
00:22:08,991 --> 00:22:12,374
were going to be and to get an overall feel of the character going and

414
00:22:13,354 --> 00:22:17,718
It's basically just whipping something up really fast without spending weeks of animation time on their first

415
00:22:17,858 --> 00:22:21,922
And it was just a simple way of communicating the ID without just words or pictures

416
00:22:21,942 --> 00:22:25,985
So everybody's like got a very clear view of what this thing was going to be

417
00:22:31,604 --> 00:22:33,625
So finally, now that everybody had a good idea of what the

418
00:22:33,665 --> 00:22:36,125
machine would look and feel like, instead of just going in

419
00:22:36,165 --> 00:22:38,066
and animating all the individual cycles and

420
00:22:38,126 --> 00:22:41,107
animation sets, we started with something which we call

421
00:22:41,127 --> 00:22:42,127
the personality test.

422
00:22:42,167 --> 00:22:44,768
And that was just to see if we can actually capture the

423
00:22:44,828 --> 00:22:47,109
personality and the behavior that you just saw in the

424
00:22:47,369 --> 00:22:50,670
previous slides, but then see if we can actually make a test

425
00:22:50,710 --> 00:22:51,590
animation out of it.

426
00:22:51,650 --> 00:22:54,011
And what you need to look at it is like concept art, but

427
00:22:54,031 --> 00:22:54,671
then in motion.

428
00:22:57,172 --> 00:23:00,415
just to come up with a short scenario and put all the characteristics in there.

429
00:23:00,455 --> 00:23:03,117
And it shouldn't take you more than one to four days to actually make these things.

430
00:23:03,177 --> 00:23:06,600
And it had so many advantages looking back in retrospect.

431
00:23:06,660 --> 00:23:08,422
And of course, you can actually see.

432
00:23:10,318 --> 00:23:13,140
if we could actually communicate the personalities

433
00:23:13,160 --> 00:23:14,161
that we wanted out of these things.

434
00:23:14,241 --> 00:23:16,082
But we also found that it was a lot easier

435
00:23:16,102 --> 00:23:17,803
to actually find your base poses this way.

436
00:23:18,363 --> 00:23:20,205
Instead of forcing yourself to go in and out

437
00:23:20,245 --> 00:23:21,225
of a base pose all the time,

438
00:23:21,345 --> 00:23:22,846
these things were already working in motion.

439
00:23:22,886 --> 00:23:25,348
So we just started to search for the poses

440
00:23:25,408 --> 00:23:26,489
within the movement that time.

441
00:23:26,529 --> 00:23:28,730
And it was also really nice to actually tackle

442
00:23:28,750 --> 00:23:30,971
some of the challenges and design limitations up front.

443
00:23:32,512 --> 00:23:34,914
Here's my first initial test that I did with the watcher.

444
00:23:35,014 --> 00:23:37,116
And to me, it still holds all the characteristics

445
00:23:37,156 --> 00:23:37,616
of the watcher.

446
00:23:37,636 --> 00:23:38,377
I mean, it's alert.

447
00:23:38,417 --> 00:23:39,798
It's super aware of its surroundings.

448
00:23:39,818 --> 00:23:40,699
It's very curious.

449
00:23:41,399 --> 00:23:43,681
And I just tried to get some of the group behavior in there.

450
00:23:43,701 --> 00:23:45,503
We're just posing a bunch of those guys around them.

451
00:23:45,523 --> 00:23:46,684
But you don't need to move them.

452
00:23:47,044 --> 00:23:49,546
But it instantly gives the feeling of, OK,

453
00:23:49,566 --> 00:23:51,287
these guys were close in groups.

454
00:23:51,347 --> 00:23:54,290
And let's see if I can actually play it again.

455
00:23:54,310 --> 00:23:55,190
It's not looping.

456
00:24:00,006 --> 00:24:01,727
But then the good thing is if you actually break it down,

457
00:24:01,767 --> 00:24:02,927
there's actually, like everything is in there.

458
00:24:02,947 --> 00:24:04,427
You have start animation, you have a cycle,

459
00:24:04,467 --> 00:24:06,008
you have some of the gestures going on,

460
00:24:06,048 --> 00:24:06,868
you have a run cycle.

461
00:24:06,888 --> 00:24:09,148
So what I did, I actually just chopped this up

462
00:24:09,168 --> 00:24:10,889
and put it into game and started working from there.

463
00:24:12,049 --> 00:24:14,429
Another example is with the grazer,

464
00:24:14,449 --> 00:24:15,730
and that was just more to actually get

465
00:24:15,770 --> 00:24:17,970
a skittish, nervous behavior out of this thing

466
00:24:17,990 --> 00:24:18,530
that we wanted.

467
00:24:18,650 --> 00:24:22,151
And again, just threw in a couple of extra machines

468
00:24:22,191 --> 00:24:23,531
around him to get that group behavior.

469
00:24:25,507 --> 00:24:26,208
That was basically it.

470
00:24:26,248 --> 00:24:28,250
And I was very lucky that the effects had nothing to do at

471
00:24:28,270 --> 00:24:31,273
that point, so they made this nice composition for me with

472
00:24:31,314 --> 00:24:32,255
a real-life background.

473
00:24:32,935 --> 00:24:34,217
So that helped.

474
00:24:34,677 --> 00:24:35,858
Last example is on the stalker.

475
00:24:35,878 --> 00:24:37,821
