720
00:36:14,538 --> 00:36:16,959
And these come actually standard in Morphium,

721
00:36:16,979 --> 00:36:17,840
so that was really nice.

722
00:36:17,880 --> 00:36:19,921
But besides actually just adjusting the height

723
00:36:19,941 --> 00:36:21,602
to the terrain, we also counter the body

724
00:36:21,622 --> 00:36:22,483
to the terrain angle.

725
00:36:22,503 --> 00:36:24,204
So if you're standing against the hill,

726
00:36:24,884 --> 00:36:27,566
like in this example, your body basically gets pushed forward

727
00:36:27,626 --> 00:36:29,367
to readjust for the center of gravity

728
00:36:29,427 --> 00:36:30,528
and vice versa as well.

729
00:36:30,548 --> 00:36:31,488
When you're standing downhill,

730
00:36:31,528 --> 00:36:34,290
you wanna be able to transfer your body backwards.

731
00:36:35,725 --> 00:36:37,907
And then for the feet itself, we used the terrain prediction

732
00:36:37,927 --> 00:36:40,669
setup, and these are basically just four raycasts being used

733
00:36:40,689 --> 00:36:42,630
from under the ball of the feet, and they just snap the

734
00:36:42,670 --> 00:36:43,330
feet to the ground.

735
00:36:44,971 --> 00:36:49,234
The only thing is, what we ran into, is that the terrain

736
00:36:49,274 --> 00:36:52,616
prediction is basically a two-bone IK solver, and more

737
00:36:53,297 --> 00:36:55,298
of them is just made for humans and not for creatures.

738
00:36:55,338 --> 00:36:59,121
So we just had to get this three-bone IK solver,

739
00:36:59,541 --> 00:37:01,662
especially for the back legs, because they have a

740
00:37:01,702 --> 00:37:02,243
different setup.

741
00:37:02,283 --> 00:37:04,004
So we came up with this.

742
00:37:05,405 --> 00:37:09,226
in a two-way, so we put helper joints in our rigs,

743
00:37:09,606 --> 00:37:12,207
and next to that, our tools department actually wrote

744
00:37:12,707 --> 00:37:13,888
something that we call an end node.

745
00:37:13,948 --> 00:37:16,529
And it's all based around the following theory.

746
00:37:16,609 --> 00:37:18,849
If you look at the back legs of a quadruped,

747
00:37:19,770 --> 00:37:21,810
basically the femur and the metatarsal

748
00:37:21,870 --> 00:37:23,411
stay close or parallel to each other.

749
00:37:23,431 --> 00:37:24,571
And it's basically like a folding chair

750
00:37:24,631 --> 00:37:25,792
going in and out all the time.

751
00:37:27,372 --> 00:37:29,915
It's both in stretched and in squashed position.

752
00:37:29,935 --> 00:37:33,098
So with that in mind, we created these helper joints

753
00:37:33,118 --> 00:37:34,800
in the back leg, which you can actually see highlighted

754
00:37:34,860 --> 00:37:35,660
in green in the movie.

755
00:37:36,221 --> 00:37:38,183
And the idea behind the helper joints was to actually

756
00:37:38,223 --> 00:37:40,085
create a two-bone IK solver that supports

757
00:37:40,125 --> 00:37:41,026
the three-bone setup.

758
00:37:41,807 --> 00:37:45,090
And the length of that first helper joint

759
00:37:45,150 --> 00:37:46,551
is basically A and C combined.

760
00:37:47,909 --> 00:37:50,231
and that actually always stays parallel to joint C.

761
00:37:51,612 --> 00:37:52,913
So that actually helped us to determine

762
00:37:52,933 --> 00:37:54,715
what the maximum stretch of this thing was gonna be.

763
00:37:55,235 --> 00:37:56,696
And next to that, like I said,

764
00:37:56,736 --> 00:37:59,438
our tools department actually wrote an end node in Morpheme

765
00:37:59,538 --> 00:38:02,361
and what the end node did was try to keep the same angle

766
00:38:02,401 --> 00:38:03,722
between the joints all the time.

767
00:38:03,942 --> 00:38:05,743
So it doesn't really matter if you have three joints

768
00:38:05,763 --> 00:38:07,104
or like 10 joints or 15 joints,

769
00:38:07,124 --> 00:38:09,967
it always tries to keep the same angle on every joint.

770
00:38:10,667 --> 00:38:12,708
Which is based on that theory, like I said, with the folding

771
00:38:12,748 --> 00:38:12,948
chair.

772
00:38:13,008 --> 00:38:15,028
So if you have those two combined, we were actually

773
00:38:15,068 --> 00:38:17,569
able to snap the feet to the terrain.

774
00:38:17,949 --> 00:38:20,470
And it actually was holding itself pretty well without

775
00:38:20,530 --> 00:38:22,750
just going nuts all over the place with these weird angles

776
00:38:22,790 --> 00:38:24,591
in the knees and in the ankles and stuff like that.

777
00:38:25,471 --> 00:38:29,132
And the last example that I want to show is how we had to

778
00:38:29,192 --> 00:38:31,233
work with longer necks when dealing with our look at

779
00:38:31,273 --> 00:38:32,613
targets that were being set by AI.

780
00:38:32,953 --> 00:38:36,314
And basically,

781
00:38:37,563 --> 00:38:38,603
This wasn't really working out.

782
00:38:38,663 --> 00:38:41,164
So we first made everything animation driven and it was

783
00:38:41,224 --> 00:38:42,525
causing for a lot of problems.

784
00:38:42,985 --> 00:38:45,806
So normally when you actually, for example, make a turn on

785
00:38:45,846 --> 00:38:49,408
spot is you want the head to actually lead the action and

786
00:38:49,808 --> 00:38:51,208
show the intention of the machine.

787
00:38:51,248 --> 00:38:53,569
But since our look at target is being set from the

788
00:38:53,629 --> 00:38:55,970
direction where the root point is pointing, which is that

789
00:38:56,030 --> 00:38:59,452
yellow arrow that you see in the top view, you can see that

790
00:38:59,472 --> 00:39:02,373
the head is already far more rotated from the position where

791
00:39:02,393 --> 00:39:03,253
the root bone is.

792
00:39:03,293 --> 00:39:05,374
So we ended up with getting these double calculated

793
00:39:05,414 --> 00:39:07,155
rotation on the neck, as you can see in here.

794
00:39:09,170 --> 00:39:12,190
And it's always off, and sometimes it actually turned

795
00:39:12,210 --> 00:39:13,191
inside of its own body.

796
00:39:13,231 --> 00:39:14,591
So this wasn't really working out for us.

797
00:39:14,631 --> 00:39:16,771
And then the solution that we actually tried after this was

798
00:39:17,252 --> 00:39:19,492
to have a fully overridden IK system.

799
00:39:20,352 --> 00:39:23,013
But that basically ended up with losing all

800
00:39:23,033 --> 00:39:23,853
the data on the neck.

801
00:39:24,253 --> 00:39:26,214
So we had a really nice animated body, and then the

802
00:39:26,254 --> 00:39:27,434
neck was just completely static.

803
00:39:27,474 --> 00:39:28,694
So that wasn't really working out either.

804
00:39:28,734 --> 00:39:31,295
And eventually we came up with the solution of adding

805
00:39:31,415 --> 00:39:32,915
additive rotations on the joints to

806
00:39:32,955 --> 00:39:34,155
replace our IK system.

807
00:39:34,175 --> 00:39:37,256
So we basically still animate our robots like you saw in the

808
00:39:37,296 --> 00:39:37,896
first example.

809
00:39:39,417 --> 00:39:41,077
But then once we were done with an animation,

810
00:39:41,117 --> 00:39:43,178
we just basically just took out all the Z rotations

811
00:39:43,218 --> 00:39:44,959
on the neck, so it looks really weird like this,

812
00:39:45,039 --> 00:39:48,120
but you basically just end up with up and down

813
00:39:48,181 --> 00:39:49,441
and tilt animations on your neck,

814
00:39:49,921 --> 00:39:51,502
and AI programmed it in such a way

815
00:39:51,542 --> 00:39:52,823
that the target is actually being set

816
00:39:52,863 --> 00:39:53,983
before they play an action.

817
00:39:54,563 --> 00:39:55,904
So the head is still leading the motion,

818
00:39:55,984 --> 00:39:57,344
the only thing is that it's AI driven

819
00:39:57,385 --> 00:39:58,505
instead of animation driven.

820
00:40:00,804 --> 00:40:03,986
And if we actually needed a full control over the head

821
00:40:04,026 --> 00:40:07,348
and the neck, we had this thing in our markup files

822
00:40:07,388 --> 00:40:09,769
where we could actually disable the head IK system.

823
00:40:09,789 --> 00:40:13,231
That way we can actually blend in and out of the head IK.

824
00:40:13,651 --> 00:40:15,312
And then you basically just end up with this result.

825
00:40:17,851 --> 00:40:19,694
And it's basically just AI setting the targets.

826
00:40:19,754 --> 00:40:22,478
And we also took out the neck rotation

827
00:40:22,738 --> 00:40:25,462
on all these 90 degrees and 180 degree cycles.

828
00:40:26,143 --> 00:40:28,346
So we could actually really keep that focus on alloy

829
00:40:28,366 --> 00:40:29,688
as they're sort of like swaving around

830
00:40:29,708 --> 00:40:31,671
to really get that predatory feel in the machines.

831
00:40:33,221 --> 00:40:35,242
And here's a quick overview of the setup in Morpheme.

832
00:40:35,262 --> 00:40:37,243
So again, the colored skeleton is basically

833
00:40:37,263 --> 00:40:39,184
your original animation, and then the white skeleton

834
00:40:39,224 --> 00:40:41,325
is the result after the target is being set.

835
00:40:41,365 --> 00:40:43,806
And as you can see, we're not just affecting the neck,

836
00:40:44,126 --> 00:40:46,588
but also the chest and the spine to some degree,

837
00:40:46,608 --> 00:40:49,369
so you have that really nice lean into the motion

838
00:40:49,389 --> 00:40:50,370
when they're looking left and right.

839
00:40:53,238 --> 00:40:55,580
So once we had all our animation blocked out,

840
00:40:55,660 --> 00:40:57,442
and all this tech was up and running,

841
00:40:58,022 --> 00:41:00,104
we could start our polish pass in the beta period.

842
00:41:00,224 --> 00:41:02,927
And because the game had such a long track,

843
00:41:03,387 --> 00:41:05,049
we knew a lot of balancing and tweaking

844
00:41:05,549 --> 00:41:07,070
needed to happen near the end of the project.

845
00:41:07,110 --> 00:41:10,193
So what we did, we just blocked in the attack super rough,

846
00:41:10,473 --> 00:41:12,295
and made sure that all the movement and gestures

847
00:41:12,335 --> 00:41:14,517
and the hit reactions were already pretty much done

848
00:41:15,318 --> 00:41:16,639
by the time we actually hit alpha.

849
00:41:17,079 --> 00:41:18,641
So at that point, we could have basically

850
00:41:19,522 --> 00:41:22,424
focus our beta phase only worrying about

851
00:41:23,084 --> 00:41:25,346
polishing these attacks and making sure that this was

852
00:41:25,366 --> 00:41:27,307
happening while the tweaking and the balancing of the game

853
00:41:27,368 --> 00:41:28,168
is happening as well.

854
00:41:28,228 --> 00:41:33,132
So the goal of the attacks, of course, like with any game,

855
00:41:33,192 --> 00:41:35,373
is make it look clear and readable from any angle.

856
00:41:35,934 --> 00:41:38,176
But we really started to look at it from a front perspective.

857
00:41:39,285 --> 00:41:41,927
since 85 to 90% of our attacks are being played

858
00:41:41,947 --> 00:41:43,628
from a front perspective, so we really wanted to get

859
00:41:43,648 --> 00:41:45,709
that asymmetry and opening up the body

860
00:41:45,729 --> 00:41:46,589
from that perspective.

861
00:41:47,110 --> 00:41:49,931
So here's an example of the earliest bite swipe

862
00:41:49,951 --> 00:41:52,653
of the Ravager, and it's not the prettiest animation,

863
00:41:52,713 --> 00:41:54,334
but it works for game design.

864
00:41:54,674 --> 00:41:56,595
It basically has the anticipation that they want,

865
00:41:56,975 --> 00:41:58,296
the forward movement and distance,

866
00:41:58,716 --> 00:42:00,077
and also the timing for the settle.

867
00:42:00,217 --> 00:42:02,218
But if you look at it from a front perspective,

868
00:42:02,238 --> 00:42:04,179
there's basically no sense of forward motion

869
00:42:04,199 --> 00:42:05,080
in this thing whatsoever.

870
00:42:05,680 --> 00:42:07,644
It all looks very boring and symmetrical as well.

871
00:42:07,965 --> 00:42:09,789
And the thing that I hated the most about this thing

872
00:42:09,829 --> 00:42:11,692
is that you're actually losing the weight

873
00:42:11,713 --> 00:42:12,534
in that jump forward.

874
00:42:12,594 --> 00:42:14,238
It just gets transferred so quickly.

875
00:42:14,298 --> 00:42:16,422
So when we started polishing, it became like this.

876
00:42:18,322 --> 00:42:20,123
So I open up the character in sideways

877
00:42:21,143 --> 00:42:22,404
to make the body a lot more readable,

878
00:42:22,424 --> 00:42:24,185
but then I put in a moving anticipation

879
00:42:24,225 --> 00:42:25,926
instead of like that holding anticipation,

880
00:42:25,946 --> 00:42:27,227
so we're closing the gap already.

881
00:42:27,887 --> 00:42:29,788
So we can actually add a lot more weight into the jump

882
00:42:30,109 --> 00:42:32,210
since we don't have to cover that much ground anymore.

883
00:42:32,870 --> 00:42:34,891
We really started to look at clear lines of actions,

884
00:42:35,232 --> 00:42:36,432
so in this case it's very clear

885
00:42:36,512 --> 00:42:37,873
from screen right to screen left,

886
00:42:37,993 --> 00:42:40,455
and in the end just add some characteristics

887
00:42:40,475 --> 00:42:41,295
with a little head shake

888
00:42:41,315 --> 00:42:43,597
and then you have your polished version.

889
00:42:43,997 --> 00:42:44,998
Again, open up the machine.

890
00:42:46,371 --> 00:42:50,874
close in and then have that really nice clear line of action and then a nice way to jump in there.

891
00:43:01,592 --> 00:43:04,253
So yeah, like I said, very clear from every angle now.

892
00:43:05,313 --> 00:43:07,553
The beak set for the long leg, same trick, right?

893
00:43:07,573 --> 00:43:08,914
It's super boring to look at,

894
00:43:08,954 --> 00:43:10,274
but it does the trick for game design

895
00:43:10,774 --> 00:43:11,994
to start testing out the combat.

896
00:43:12,014 --> 00:43:14,695
And it was also very easy for us to just adjust this

897
00:43:14,715 --> 00:43:17,576
within a couple of minutes and then put it back in game again

898
00:43:17,676 --> 00:43:19,276
so that they were happy with all the timings

899
00:43:19,376 --> 00:43:20,716
and distances and stuff like that.

900
00:43:20,756 --> 00:43:22,757
But once we start polishing it,

901
00:43:23,677 --> 00:43:25,157
I open up the character again from the start

902
00:43:25,197 --> 00:43:26,077
for a better silhouette,

903
00:43:26,137 --> 00:43:28,278
and then follow up with that nice clean line of action

904
00:43:28,338 --> 00:43:29,758
going from screen right to screen left.

905
00:43:30,839 --> 00:43:33,642
If you look at it from slow motion,

906
00:43:33,702 --> 00:43:34,843
open up the character, close in,

907
00:43:35,083 --> 00:43:36,565
really present what you're gonna attack with,

908
00:43:36,625 --> 00:43:39,508
and then strong line of action to finish the job,

909
00:43:39,608 --> 00:43:41,250
and nice weighty jump again.

910
00:43:42,572 --> 00:43:43,793
And then this is the end resulting game.

911
00:43:44,934 --> 00:43:46,797
And as you can see, I really emphasized

912
00:43:46,837 --> 00:43:48,999
that motion going upwards.

913
00:43:49,838 --> 00:43:52,279
And then to keep the same angle that he's going in,

914
00:43:52,339 --> 00:43:54,981
just because the player actually might miss the attack

915
00:43:55,221 --> 00:43:57,122
since they're dodging or there's so much effects

916
00:43:57,182 --> 00:43:59,623
or rake as being projected on the screen

917
00:43:59,663 --> 00:44:00,484
that they might miss it.

918
00:44:00,504 --> 00:44:03,345
So as long as you keep that swiping motion upwards,

919
00:44:03,385 --> 00:44:04,966
the player still registers what's going on.

920
00:44:06,487 --> 00:44:07,528
And then the last example,

921
00:44:08,908 --> 00:44:10,289
for the tail swipe on the snap mod,

922
00:44:10,309 --> 00:44:12,110
this was actually a lot clearer from the start already,

923
00:44:12,690 --> 00:44:13,371
when I look back at it,

924
00:44:13,411 --> 00:44:15,492
but I really wanted to push that swiping motion

925
00:44:15,512 --> 00:44:16,753
in terms of that tail being whipped.

926
00:44:18,154 --> 00:44:20,455
So this is what it ended up with.

927
00:44:20,495 --> 00:44:21,916
And as you can see, the tail's already coming up

928
00:44:21,936 --> 00:44:22,917
from a front perspective,

929
00:44:22,937 --> 00:44:24,518
so the player gets to see what's coming.

930
00:44:24,598 --> 00:44:28,420
And then I open up that character completely right there

931
00:44:28,460 --> 00:44:29,881
before he actually slams down again.

932
00:44:30,101 --> 00:44:32,542
And the biggest difference,

933
00:44:32,722 --> 00:44:34,783
that game design actually wanted this thing to face forward

934
00:44:34,903 --> 00:44:37,205
instead of with his back towards Aloy again,

935
00:44:37,225 --> 00:44:38,725
so we added that turn in as well in the end.

936
00:44:40,106 --> 00:44:40,386
So again.

937
00:44:41,638 --> 00:44:44,300
clearly present the tail, strong poses,

938
00:44:44,340 --> 00:44:46,682
and then finish off with a strong line of action

939
00:44:46,742 --> 00:44:48,963
so that it's always clear what's happening

940
00:44:48,983 --> 00:44:51,825
towards the player in that turn.

941
00:44:51,845 --> 00:44:53,627
And then this is your end result in game.

942
00:44:54,627 --> 00:44:57,029
And even like effects is actually emphasizing these attacks

943
00:44:57,069 --> 00:44:58,510
with all the motion trails going on.

944
00:44:58,570 --> 00:45:01,092
So even though there's so much noise going on,

945
00:45:01,593 --> 00:45:03,374
hopefully the player just always registers

946
00:45:03,454 --> 00:45:06,416
what's being attacked with and what the attack actually is.

947
00:45:09,029 --> 00:45:11,070
Basically 80% of the polish was spent on this.

948
00:45:11,110 --> 00:45:13,371
So we just went through every attack for every machine

949
00:45:13,451 --> 00:45:15,412
and then just really started to break it down.

950
00:45:16,132 --> 00:45:18,133
Okay, what is it that we wanna make clear?

951
00:45:18,393 --> 00:45:19,553
Start looking from the front angle

952
00:45:19,613 --> 00:45:21,594
and then really start polishing things up from there.

953
00:45:23,355 --> 00:45:25,155
Also, since there was so much balancing going on,

954
00:45:25,475 --> 00:45:27,436
this is where you can actually really start playing around

955
00:45:28,496 --> 00:45:29,177
with your animation.

956
00:45:29,217 --> 00:45:30,917
And we just broke it up into three sections, so

957
00:45:31,577 --> 00:45:33,178
anticipation, attack, and settle, of course.

958
00:45:33,198 --> 00:45:34,839
And that's where you can really start playing with your

959
00:45:35,179 --> 00:45:36,099
timing and spacing.

960
00:45:36,159 --> 00:45:39,500
And basically, the remaining 20% was spent on whatever

961
00:45:39,520 --> 00:45:43,541
looked out of place or whatever wasn't up to standard.

962
00:45:43,581 --> 00:45:45,142
And to give you just one example of that.

963
00:45:48,202 --> 00:45:51,786
One of the issues we actually ran into was that the machines

964
00:45:51,806 --> 00:45:54,329
were way too overactive and that the movement was actually

965
00:45:54,349 --> 00:45:55,109
too big as well.

966
00:45:55,190 --> 00:45:59,334
So the hardest part about that was that the weak spots

967
00:45:59,454 --> 00:46:01,316
almost became impossible to shoot for the player.

968
00:46:01,376 --> 00:46:05,881
So both AI and animation had to tone it down very

969
00:46:05,901 --> 00:46:06,341
drastically.

970
00:46:06,381 --> 00:46:08,143
And even if we were pretty happy with the movement

971
00:46:08,163 --> 00:46:09,644
sometimes, it was a bit of a pain.

972
00:46:10,025 --> 00:46:13,387
If the player has a bad time, you're basically just screwing up as an animator and developer.

973
00:46:13,428 --> 00:46:15,089
So you have to really take care of that.

974
00:46:15,149 --> 00:46:18,311
